Name: ros_publisher_factory
Return: A ros publisher handle with the methods "publish(myStruct)"/"write(myStruct)" and "close()"
Comment: Used to create a ROS2 publisher handle that can be used to publish or write messages to the topic.

Parameters.Label: topic
Parameters.Comment: The name of the topic.

Parameters.Label: type
Parameters.Comment: The type of the messages on the topic. A dynamic library corresponding to the type must be present on the robot, e.g libstd_msgs__rosidl_typesupport_introspection_c.so for std_msgs/String.

Parameters.Label: history
Parameters.Comment: How many messages to store in the history. Options are "default", "keep_last" and "keep_all".

Parameters.Label: depth
Parameters.Comment: The size of the queue of old messages. It requires history to be "keep_last" to take effect.

Parameters.Label: reliability
Parameters.Comment: How reliable the topic should be. Options are "default", "reliable", and "best_effort".

Parameters.Label: durability
Parameters.Comment: Options are "default", "transient_local", and "volatile".

Parameters.Label: deadline
Parameters.Comment: A contract for how much time is allowed between messages.

Parameters.Label: lifespan
Parameters.Comment: The amount of time a message will be considered valid. 0 will mean lifespan is disabled.

Parameters.Label: liveliness
Parameters.Comment: Specifies for how long the publisher is considered alive. Options are "default", "automatic", and "manual".

Parameters.Label: lease_duration
Parameters.Comment: The period of time a publisher has to indicate that it is alive before it is considered to have lost liveliness.

Name: ros_subscriber_factory
Return: A ros subscriber handle with the methods "read()", "read_history(number_of_msgs)", "wait(timeout)" and "close"
Comment: Used to create a subscriber handle. The constraints on the message type from publishers also apply to subscribers, but the read method returns a struct corresponding to the message type, blocking until one is available.
